    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:eaa0a255-00dd-48c9-8f77-42acd21bdb50",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 55-year-old Czech woman with a slightly rounded face, medium build, and tired eyes that hint at several weeks of interrupted sleep. She works as an administrative assistant in a Prague insurance company, spending most of her day seated at a desk. Outside of work she enjoys weekend hiking in the Šumava highlands and tending to her balcony herb garden. She lives with her adult daughter and keeps a close-knit circle of colleagues and neighbours.\n\nFor the past six weeks {patientName} has been troubled by persistent abdominal pain localised to the epigastrium [SNOMED:K29.7], accompanied by nausea after meals [SNOMED:K29.7], excessive belching [SNOMED:K29.7], and a distressing sense of abdominal bloating [SNOMED:K29.7]. She reports early satiety [SNOMED:K29.7], meaning she can eat only small portions before feeling uncomfortably full. Occasional vomiting has occurred two or three times per week [SNOMED:K29.7]. She describes the pain as a dull, gnawing pressure beneath her sternum that worsens roughly an hour after meals [MEDDIALOG:K29.7:3].\n\n{patientName} admits to a long habit of drinking two to three cups of strong black coffee daily and frequently eating spicy, fatty foods at work canteen lunches [MEDDIALOG:K29.7:4]. She has been under considerable work-related stress this year and confesses she often forgets to eat breakfast, going long hours on an empty stomach. She does not smoke and drinks wine only occasionally at family gatherings. She is not currently taking any regular prescription medications but has been self-medicating with over-the-counter ibuprofen for occasional knee pain, a recognised aggravating factor for gastric mucosal inflammation [MEDDIALOG:K29.7:3]."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:db4d5c54-ae9a-47c6-b9b9-84ceaa1aba40",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no prior hospitalisation for gastrointestinal complaints, though she recalls a brief episode of stomach upset three years ago that resolved spontaneously. She was investigated for cholelithiasis in 2018 and subsequently underwent laparoscopic cholecystectomy. She has no known history of peptic ulcer disease, celiac disease, or inflammatory bowel disease. She has mild hypertension managed with lifestyle measures alone. She is post-menopausal since age 51 with no hormone replacement therapy.\n\nLifestyle risk factors include regular NSAID use (ibuprofen for knee pain) [MEDDIALOG:K29.7:3], high coffee intake, and a diet rich in spicy, fatty foods [MEDDIALOG:K29.7:4]. {patientName} denies significant alcohol use and has never smoked. Family history is notable for her mother having been diagnosed with gastric ulcer disease in her sixties and her father dying of colorectal cancer at age 72, motivating {patientName} to seek thorough gastroenterological evaluation. {patientName} is allergic to amoxicillin (urticaria) and has a known food intolerance to cow's milk causing bloating and nausea [SNOMED:K29.7]."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}